util.object

Interface Identifiable


  • public interface Identifiable
    A way to identify an object in a given context.

    • Method Summary

      default int hashedId(int size)

    • Method Detail

      • id

        default java.lang.String id()
        Produces the unique ID that identifies this object in some given context. This method is defaulted to return the string fqn@ref, where fqn is the fully qualified class name of this object and ref is the HEX representation of this object's native hash code (i.e. what is returned by identityHashCode) which is usually the memory address of the object. This is the same of what toString returns if it has not been overwritten and hashCode has not been overwritten either.
        Returns:
        this object's ID.

      • hashedId

        default int hashedId(int size)
        Hashes this object's ID so that the returned code is in the range [0, size - 1] (endpoints are included). This method is defaulted to use a hash function that assumes the ID's are bounded-length strings occurring with uniform probability. This would likely be the case for UUID's, but in general you should provide a suitable implementation depending on the type of ID you're using.
        Parameters:
        size - the number of buckets for the hash function, i.e. the size of the codomain.
        Returns:
        the hashed ID.
